63","1194":"1194","1172":"1172","1193":"1193","Abt 1228":"circa 1228","1290":"1290","1228":"1228","1206":"1206","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1232":"1232","Of, Winwick, Northamptonshire, England":"Winwick, Northamptonshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Winwick, Northamptonshire, England":"Winwick, Northamptonshire, England"},"en":{"1194–":"1194–Deceased","1194–Male":"1194–Deceased","1206–Female":"1206–Deceased","1228–Male":"1228–Deceased","1232–1286":"1232–1286","1163–1200":"1163–1200","1172–1194":"1172–1194","Abt 1227":"about 1227","1286":"1286","1163":"1163","1194":"1194","1172":"1172","1193":"1193","Abt 1228":"about 1228","1290":"1290","1228":"1228","1206":"1206","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1232":"1232","Of, Winwick, Northamptonshire, England":"Winwick, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Winwick, Northamptonshire, England":"Winwick, Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Andrews","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Andrew  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This is the usual southern English patronymic form, also found in Wales; the Scottish and northern English form is   Anderson  . In North America, this surname has absorbed various cognates from other languages, e.g. Polish   Andrzejewski  , Slovenian <b>Andrejčič</b>, Serbian and Croatian <b>Andrić</b> (see   Andric  ), and Czech <b>Ondráček</b> (see   Ondracek  ).","Irish and Scottish: Anglicized form of Scottish Gaelic <b>Mac Aindreis</b> or Irish <b>Mac Aindriú</b>, see   McAndrew  .","History: This was a common name among the early settlers in New England. Robert Andrews emigrated in 1635 from Norwich, England, to Ipswich, MA. Even before 1635, one Thomas Andrews is recorded as being established in Hingham. A certain William Andrews was a member of John Davenport's company, which sailed from Boston in 1638 to found the New Haven colony."],"variants":[{"name":"Andrus","meanings":["English: variant of   Andrews  .","History: William Andrus came to Boston in 1635 and moved to New Haven in 1639, where he died in 1676."]},{"name":"Andrew","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the usual vernacular English form (recorded from the 13th century onward) of the New Testament Greek personal name   Andreas  . In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed many cognates from other languages, e.g. Czech <b>Ondřej</b> (see   Ondrey  ) and Albanian   Ndreu  , and also their patronymics and other derivatives (see examples at   Andrews  ).","History: The surname Andrew was first brought to North America from England by Robert Andrew (died 1668), who settled in Boxford, MA."]},{"name":"Andros","meanings":["English: variant of   Andrews  . This surname is very rare in Britain.","American shortened form of Greek <b>Andronikos</b> (see   Andron   2) or of any other surname based on a personal name beginning with <i>Andr-</i> (from <i>andros</i>, genitive of <i>anēr</i> ‘man, male’), e.g. <b>Androutsos</b>, including their patronymics and other derivatives, such as <b>Andronikidis</b>.","History: William Andros came to VA in 1617 and died there <i>c.</i> 1655. Sir Edmund Andros (1637–1714) was the British colonial governor of several provinces in America between 1674 and 1698, most notably NY (1674–81)."]}]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":21,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":30,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":65,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":96,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When George Andrews , Esq. was born in 1194, in Winwick, Northamptonshire, England, his father, Sir, Thomas Andrews , II, Knight, was 31 and his mother, Lady Johanna Cantilupe Breasey, was 22. He married Lady Marguerite Burford about 1227, in Northamptonshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1194–":"1194–Surnud","1194–Male":"1194–Surnud","1206–Female":"1206–Surnud","1228–Male":"1228–Surnud","1232–1286":"1232–1286","1163–1200":"1163–1200","1172–1194":"1172–1194","Abt 1227":"umbes 1227","1286":"1286","1163":"1163","1194":"1194","1172":"1172","1193":"1193","Abt 1228":"umbes 1228","1290":"1290","1228":"1228","1206":"1206","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1232":"1232","Of, Winwick, Northamptonshire, England":"Winwick, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Winwick, Northamptonshire, England":"Winwick, Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"1194–":"1194–Kuollut","1194–Male":"1194–Kuollut","1206–Female":"1206–Kuollut","1228–Male":"1228–Kuollut","1232–1286":"1232–1286","1163–1200":"1163–1200","1172–1194":"1172–1194","Abt 1227":"noin 1227","1286":"1286","1163":"1163","1194":"1194","1172":"1172","1193":"1193","Abt 1228":"noin 1228","1290":"1290","1228":"1228","1206":"1206","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1232":"1232","Of, Winwick, Northamptonshire, England":"Winwick, Northamptonshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Winwick, Northamptonshire, England":"Winwick, Northamptonshire, England"},"fr":{"1194–":"1194–Décédé","1194–Male":"1194–Décédé","1206–Female":"1206–Décédée","1228–Male":"1228–Décédé","1232–1286":"1232–1286","1163–1200":"1163–1200","1172–1194":"1172–11